mitre_attack_techniques.signature_description: Adversaries may bypass UAC mechanisms to elevate process privileges on system.
Adversaries may configure system settings to automatically execute a program during system boot or logon to maintain persistence or gain higher-level privileges on compromised systems.
Adversaries may inject code into processes in order to evade process-based defenses as well as possibly elevate privileges.
Adversaries may circumvent mechanisms designed to control elevate privileges to gain higher-level permissions.
Adversaries may establish persistence and/or elevate privileges by executing malicious content triggered by Image File Execution Options (IFEO) debuggers.
Adversaries may achieve persistence by adding a program to a startup folder or referencing it with a Registry run key.
Adversaries may establish persistence and/or elevate privileges using system mechanisms that trigger execution based on specific events.
Adversaries may abuse utilities that allow for command execution to bypass security restrictions that limit the use of command-line interpreters.

Adversaries may interact with the Windows Registry to hide configuration information within Registry keys, remove information as part of cleaning up, or as part of other techniques to aid in persistence and execution.
Adversaries may communicate using application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic.
Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries.
Executes batch files
Uses cmd line tools excessively to alter registry or file data
Creates or modifies windows services
Spawns drivers
Tries to load missing DLLs
Creates an undocumented autostart registry key
Changes image file execution options
Disables UAC (registry)

Queries a list of all running drivers

sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects the registration of a debugger for a program that is available in the logon screen (sticky key backdoor).
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems), oscd.community, Jonhnathan Ribeiro

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Potential Tampering With RDP Related Registry Keys Via Reg.EXE
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects the execution of "reg.exe" for enabling/disabling the RDP service on the host by tampering with the 'CurrentControlSet\Control\Terminal Server' values
Detects when an attacker tries to disable User Account Control (UAC) by setting the registry value "EnableLUA" to 0.
Detects modification of autostart extensibility point (ASEP) in registry.
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Victor Sergeev, Daniil Yugoslavskiy, Gleb Sukhodolskiy, Timur Zinniatullin, oscd.community, Tim Shelton, frack113 (split)

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: RDP Sensitive Settings Changed to Zero
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects tampering of RDP Terminal Service/Server sensitive settings.
Such as allowing unauthorized users access to a system via the 'fAllowUnsolicited' or enabling RDP via 'fDenyTSConnections', etc.
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Samir Bousseaden, David ANDRE, Roberto Rodriguez @Cyb3rWard0g, Nasreddine Bencherchali
